04428nam a22006615i 9780292796980DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927969807 a10.7560/7064532doi  a(DE-B1597)587576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a820.9/112221 aHopkins, Lisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScreening the Gothic /cLisa Hopkins. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The gothic Towards a Definition -- tChapter One. Gothic revenants: A Tale of Three Hamlets -- tChapter Two. Putting the gothic in: Clarissa, Sense and Sensibility, Mansfield Park, and TheTime Machine -- tChapter Three. Taking the gothic out: ’Tis Pity She’s a Whore, Mary Shelley’s Frankenstein, TheWoman in White, and Lady Audley’s Secret -- tChapter Four. Fragmenting the gothic: Jane Eyre and Dracula -- tChapter Five. Gothic and the family: The Mummy Returns, Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone, andThe Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFilmmakers have long been drawn to the Gothic with its eerie settings and promise of horror lurking beneath the surface. Moreover, the Gothic allows filmmakers to hold a mirror up to their own age and reveal society's deepest fears. Franco Zeffirelli's Jane Eyre, Francis Ford Coppola's Bram Stoker's Dracula, and Kenneth Branagh's Hamlet are just a few examples of film adaptations of literary Gothic texts. In this ground-breaking study, Lisa Hopkins explores how the Gothic has been deployed in these and other contemporary films and comes to some surprising conclusions. For instance, in a brilliant chapter on films geared to children, Hopkins finds that horror resides not in the trolls, wizards, and goblins that abound in Harry Potter, but in the heart of the family. Screening the Gothic offers a radical new way of understanding the relationship between film and the Gothic as it surveys a wide range of films, many of which have received scant critical attention. Its central claim is that, paradoxically, those texts whose affiliations with the Gothic were the clearest became the least Gothic when filmed. Thus, Hopkins surprises readers by revealing Gothic elements in films such as Sense and Sensibility and Mansfield Park, as well as exploring more obviously Gothic films like The Mummy and The Fellowship of the Ring. Written in an accessible and engaging manner, Screening the Gothic will be of interest to film lovers as well as students and scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aEnglish literaturevAdaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexFilm adaptations. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aFilm adaptations. 0aGothic revival (Literature)zGreat Britain. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror tales, EnglishxFilm adaptations. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796980/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK